## Core Strategies

### 1. Entity-First Content Structure

AI systems recognize and connect entities. Structure content around clear entities:

```markdown
# [Entity Name] - What It Is and How It Works

## Definition
[Clear, concise definition in 1-2 sentences]

## Key Facts
- Fact 1: [Specific, verifiable information]
- Fact 2: [With numbers/dates when possible]
- Fact 3: [Attribution to authoritative sources]

## How [Entity] Works
[Step-by-step explanation]

## Comparison with Alternatives
| Feature | [Entity] | Alternative A | Alternative B |
|---------|----------|---------------|---------------|

## Common Questions
### What is [Entity]?
[Direct answer]

### How do I use [Entity]?
[Step-by-step guide]

## Sources & References
- [Authoritative Source 1](url)
- [Authoritative Source 2](url)
```

### 2. Answer-Optimized Content

Structure content to directly answer questions:

```tsx
// FAQ component optimized for AI extraction
export function FAQSection({ faqs }: { faqs: FAQ[] }) {
  return (
    <section itemScope itemType="https://schema.org/FAQPage">
      <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
      {faqs.map((faq, index) => (
        <article
          key={index}
          itemScope
          itemProp="mainEntity"
          itemType="https://schema.org/Question"
        >
          <h3 itemProp="name">{faq.question}</h3>
          <div
            itemScope
            itemProp="acceptedAnswer"
            itemType="https://schema.org/Answer"
          >
            <div itemProp="text">
              {/* First sentence should be the direct answer */}
              <p><strong>{faq.directAnswer}</strong></p>
              {/* Supporting details follow */}
              <p>{faq.elaboration}</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </article>
      ))}
    </section>
  );
}
```

### 3. Citation-Worthy Content Patterns

Make content easily citable by AI:

```markdown
## Best Practices for Citable Content

### 1. Lead with the Answer
**Good:**
> "React 18 was released on March 29, 2022, introducing concurrent rendering and automatic batching."

**Bad:**
> "In this article, we'll explore the history of React and eventually discuss when React 18 came out..."

### 2. Include Specific Data
**Good:**
> "According to the 2024 Stack Overflow survey, 40.6% of developers use React."

**Bad:**
> "React is very popular among developers."

### 3. Use Clear Attribution
**Good:**
> "The React team at Meta announced that..."

**Bad:**
> "It was announced that..."

### 4. Provide Definitions
**Good:**
> "Server Components are React components that render exclusively on the server, reducing client-side JavaScript bundle size."

**Bad:**
> "Server Components are a new feature."
```

### 4. Structured Data for AI Discovery

Enhanced Schema.org for AI comprehension:

```tsx
// Enhanced Article Schema for AI Discovery
export function AIOptimizedArticleSchema({ article }: { article: Article }) {
  const schema = {
    '@context': 'https://schema.org',
    '@type': 'Article',
    headline: article.title,
    description: article.excerpt,

    // Essential for AI discovery
    datePublished: article.publishedAt,
    dateModified: article.updatedAt,

    // Author credibility signals
    author: {
      '@type': 'Person',
      name: article.author.name,
      url: article.author.profileUrl,
      sameAs: [
        article.author.twitter,
        article.author.linkedin,
        article.author.github,
      ].filter(Boolean),
      jobTitle: article.author.title,
      worksFor: {
        '@type': 'Organization',
        name: article.author.company,
      },
    },

    // Content signals
    articleSection: article.category,
    keywords: article.tags.join(', '),
    wordCount: article.wordCount,

    // For educational/how-to content
    ...(article.type === 'how-to' && {
      '@type': 'HowTo',
      step: article.steps.map((step, index) => ({
        '@type': 'HowToStep',
        position: index + 1,
        name: step.title,
        text: step.description,
        url: `${article.url}#step-${index + 1}`,
      })),
    }),

    // Citations and sources
    citation: article.sources.map(source => ({
      '@type': 'CreativeWork',
      name: source.title,
      url: source.url,
      author: source.author,
      datePublished: source.date,
    })),

    // Speakable for voice assistants
    speakable: {
      '@type': 'SpeakableSpecification',
      cssSelector: ['.article-summary', '.key-points'],
    },
  };

  return (
    <script
      type="application/ld+json"
      dangerouslySetInnerHTML={{ __html: JSON.stringify(schema) }}
    />
  );
}
```

